Complete Command Reference with Why We Used It
1. Verify EKS Cluster
Check cluster nodes
kubectl get nodes

Why?

Verify worker nodes joined the cluster.

Output:

NAME                         STATUS
ip-192-168-x-x.ec2.internal  Ready
2. Deploy Application
Create resources
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

Why?

Creates Deployment resource in Kubernetes.
Create service
kubectl apply -f service.yaml

Why?

Expose application through ClusterIP/LoadBalancer.
3. Verify Pods
List pods
kubectl get pods

Why?

Check whether application containers are running.

Example:

Running
CrashLoopBackOff
Completed
ImagePullBackOff
Watch pod status
kubectl get pods -w

Why?

Observe pod lifecycle in real time.

Useful during rollout.

4. Investigate Pod Failures
Describe pod
kubectl describe pod POD_NAME

Why?

Shows:
- Events
- Scheduling issues
- Restart counts
- Image pull errors
- Resource problems

Used when:

CrashLoopBackOff
Completed
Pending
View logs
kubectl logs POD_NAME

Why?

See application output.

Used to find:

Python errors
Database errors
Redis errors
Import errors
Previous container logs
kubectl logs POD_NAME --previous

Why?

Pod restarted before you could inspect logs.

Very useful for CrashLoopBackOff.

5. Verify Deployment
Check deployment
kubectl get deployments

Why?

Verify desired replicas.
Rollout status
kubectl rollout status deployment/backend-deployment

Why?

Monitor deployment progress.
6. Update Image
Update image
kubectl set image deployment/backend-deployment \
backend=ACCOUNT_ID.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/backend:v2

Why?

Deploy newer image without deleting deployment.
Verify rollout
kubectl get pods -w

Why?

Observe old pods terminating and new pods starting.
7. Verify Services
List services
kubectl get svc

Why?

Check:
- ClusterIP
- LoadBalancer
- External URL

Used to obtain:

backend ELB URL
frontend ELB URL
8. Verify Connectivity
Test backend
curl http://LB_URL/api/employees

Why?

Verify API endpoint is reachable.
Test POST
curl -X POST \
-H "Content-Type: application/json" \
-d '{"name":"Alex","role":"Developer"}'

Why?

Verify inserts into database.
9. Inspect Running Container
Open shell
kubectl exec -it deployment/backend-deployment -- sh

Why?

Inspect container internals.

Used to check:

.env
app.py
config.py
DNS resolution
networking
Read files
kubectl exec -it deployment/backend-deployment \
-- cat /app/app.py

Why?

Verify deployed code matches local code.

We discovered old code versions this way.

10. Verify DNS

Inside pod:

python -c "
import socket
print(socket.gethostbyname('hostname'))
"

Why?

Check DNS resolution.

Used for Redis endpoint testing.

11. Verify TCP Connectivity

Inside pod:

import socket

s = socket.socket()
s.settimeout(5)

print(
    s.connect_ex(
      ("redis-host",6379)
    )
)

Why?

Verify network connectivity.

Result:

0 = success
11 = timeout

This helped identify Redis networking issues.

12. ECR Commands
Login
aws ecr get-login-password \
| docker login

Why?

Authenticate Docker with ECR.
Build image
docker build -t backend:v1 .

Why?

Create Docker image.
Tag image
docker tag backend:v1 \
ACCOUNT_ID.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/backend:v1

Why?

Prepare image for ECR.
Push image
docker push \
ACCOUNT_ID.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/backend:v1

Why?

Upload image to ECR.
13. AWS Networking Troubleshooting
Get EKS VPC
aws eks describe-cluster \
--name my-eks-cluster \
--query cluster.resourcesVpcConfig.vpcId

Why?

Find EKS VPC.
Get EKS Subnets
aws eks describe-cluster \
--name my-eks-cluster \
--query cluster.resourcesVpcConfig.subnetIds

Why?

Identify cluster networking.
Get ElastiCache Details
aws elasticache describe-serverless-caches

Why?

Find:
- Endpoint
- VPC
- Security Group
Check Subnet VPC
aws ec2 describe-subnets \
--subnet-ids subnet-id

Why?

Determine which VPC resources belong to.

This revealed:

EKS VPC      -> vpc-01d5...
Redis VPC    -> vpc-00513...

Root cause of timeout.

Check Security Group
aws ec2 describe-security-groups \
--group-ids sg-id

Why?

Verify inbound/outbound rules.
14. Database Troubleshooting
View table
SELECT * FROM employees;

Why?

Verify inserted records.
Check schema
SHOW CREATE TABLE employees;

Why?

Verify columns and AUTO_INCREMENT.
Show tables
SHOW TABLES;

Why?

Verify table exists.
